Note: ===================================================================
Note: DOCKERFILE SEMANTIC ANALYZER
Note: ===================================================================
Note: Semantic analysis for Dockerfile container definitions. Handles Docker
Note: instruction validation, multi-stage build analysis, layer optimization
Note: recommendations, and container security best practices.

Note: Part of the Translation System
Note: Location: compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/dockerfile/dockerfile_semantic.runa
Note: ===================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/dockerfile/dockerfile_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict

Note: ===================================================================
Note: SEMANTIC ANALYZER STRUCTURE
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Dockerfile semantic analysis tracks per-instruction state that matters
across the build: base images (FROM directives, possibly multi-stage),
named stages, exposed ports (EXPOSE), runtime ENV vars, declared VOLUMEs,
WORKDIRs, USERs, LABELs, build ARGs, the current stage cursor, and a layer
count for image-size warnings. Three parallel diagnostic streams keep
security issues, optimization advice, and hard validation errors apart so
the reporter can apply distinct severity rules.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
17 x i64 record (136 bytes, offsets 0..128): each registry slot is a Dict
(string-keyed lookups like environment_vars) or List (ordered streams like
exposed_ports/security_issues). current_stage points to the active stage
Dict during a walk; layer_count is bumped on every RUN/ADD/COPY/etc. The
error_message + has_error pair behaves identically to the cmake/cpp
analyzers (sticky first-error).
@End Implementation

Type called "DockerfileSemanticAnalyzer":
    base_images as Integer
    stages as Integer
    exposed_ports as Integer
    environment_vars as Integer
    volumes as Integer
    workdirs as Integer
    users as Integer
    labels as Integer
    args as Integer
    current_stage as Integer
    layer_count as Integer
    security_issues as Integer
    optimization_warnings as Integer
    validation_errors as Integer
    validation_warnings as Integer
    error_message as Integer
    has_error as Integer
End Type

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ANALYZER CREATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The Dockerfile analyzer is a 136-byte (17-slot) record holding 13 collection
registries plus state counters: base_images, stages, exposed_ports,
environment_vars, volumes, workdirs, users, labels, args, security_issues,
optimization_warnings, validation_errors, validation_warnings, plus
current_stage/layer_count counters and the error_message/has_error pair.
We split errors from warnings (and errors from optimization-warnings)
because Docker validation produces three severity tiers: hard syntax
errors that block builds, security issues that compromise the container,
and optimization hints that don't break anything but waste resources.
Downstream tooling treats each tier differently.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 136-byte record via Layout.allocate; returns 0 if it fails.
Creates 11 Lists (base_images, stages, exposed_ports, volumes, workdirs,
users, security_issues, optimization_warnings, validation_errors,
validation_warnings) and 3 Dicts (environment_vars, labels, args), wiring
them into the analyzer at fixed offsets 0..64. Initialises counter slots:
offset 72 (current_stage) = 0, offset 80 (layer_count) = 0, offset 120
(error_message) = 0, offset 128 (has_error) = 0. Returns the analyzer
handle as an opaque Integer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_dockerfile_semantic_analyzer" returns Integer:
    Note: Create Dockerfile semantic analyzer for container validation

    Let analyzer_size be 136
    Let analyzer be proc allocate from Layout with analyzer_size

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let base_images be proc create from List
    Let stages be proc create from List
    Let exposed_ports be proc create from List
    Let environment_vars be proc create from Dict
    Let volumes be proc create from List
    Let workdirs be proc create from List
    Let users be proc create from List
    Let labels be proc create from Dict
    Let args be proc create from Dict
    Let security_issues be proc create from List
    Let optimization_warnings be proc create from List
    Let validation_errors be proc create from List
    Let validation_warnings be proc create from List

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, base_images
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, stages
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16, exposed_ports
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24, environment_vars
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, volumes
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, workdirs
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48, users
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56, labels
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64, args
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, 0  Note: current_stage
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80, 0  Note: layer_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88, security_issues
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96, optimization_warnings
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104, validation_errors
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112, validation_warnings
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120, 0  Note: error_message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128, 0  Note: has_error

    Return analyzer
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MAIN ANALYSIS ENTRY POINT
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Sequences a six-phase analysis with strict ordering: structure validation
must run first to populate the instruction-derived registries (base_images,
exposed_ports, etc.); stage analysis follows because it depends on the
already-collected FROM list; image validation needs the populated base_images
list; security analysis must see the full instruction stream including
USER/RUN context; layer optimization comes next because it needs the
layer_count populated by structure validation; best-practices is last
because it consults every registry built by the prior phases. Each phase
runs even if earlier phases reported errors - the user wants a complete
diagnostics dump, not a fail-fast.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 immediately if analyzer is null. If dockerfile_ast is null,
calls set_dockerfile_semantic_error and returns 0. Calls in order:
validate_dockerfile_structure, analyze_build_stages, validate_base_images,
analyze_dockerfile_security, analyze_layer_optimization,
validate_docker_best_practices. After all six complete, reads has_error
(offset 128); returns 0 if any phase set it, else 1. Return value is
analysis-level success/failure; individual error and warning lists carry
the full diagnostic detail.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Dockerfile AST originates from untrusted source files. All instruction
arguments are validated before being added to the registries, and
security_issues is populated independently from validation_errors so
downstream tooling can apply security policy distinct from syntactic
correctness.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "analyze_dockerfile" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform complete semantic analysis on Dockerfile

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If dockerfile_ast is equal to 0:
        proc set_dockerfile_semantic_error with analyzer, "Null Dockerfile AST"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Phase 1: Validate instruction sequence and structure
    proc validate_dockerfile_structure with analyzer, dockerfile_ast

    Note: Phase 2: Analyze build stages and multi-stage builds
    proc analyze_build_stages with analyzer, dockerfile_ast

    Note: Phase 3: Validate base images and dependencies
    proc validate_base_images from analyzer

    Note: Phase 4: Perform security analysis
    proc analyze_dockerfile_security with analyzer, dockerfile_ast

    Note: Phase 5: Analyze layer optimization opportunities
    proc analyze_layer_optimization with analyzer, dockerfile_ast

    Note: Phase 6: Validate Docker best practices
    proc validate_docker_best_practices with analyzer, dockerfile_ast

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: DOCKERFILE STRUCTURE VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 1 validates two orthogonal properties: macro structure (FROM
placement, instruction ordering, required instructions) and micro
structure (per-instruction syntax). An empty instruction list is treated
as a hard error rather than being silently accepted, because an empty
Dockerfile produces an empty image and is almost certainly a mistake.
Order matters: FROM-placement validation runs before the per-instruction
loop so that the "FROM must come first" rule is reported before any
downstream errors that would result from a missing FROM.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads instructions list and its count via List.size. If count == 0, adds
"Empty Dockerfile" validation error and returns. Calls
validate_from_instruction_placement to enforce FROM-first / ARG-before-
FROM ordering. Then loops i in 0..count-1: pulls instruction at index,
calls validate_instruction_syntax(analyzer, instruction, i) (i used as
the 0-based line number for error reporting), and
collect_instruction_info to populate the per-instruction registries.
Finally calls validate_required_instructions for whole-file checks
(e.g., presence of CMD or ENTRYPOINT).
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_dockerfile_structure" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Validate Dockerfile instruction sequence and structure

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions from dockerfile_ast
    Let instruction_count be proc size from List with instructions

    If instruction_count is equal to 0:
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, "Empty Dockerfile"
        Return
    End If

    Note: Validate FROM instruction is first (or after ARG for build args)
    proc validate_from_instruction_placement with analyzer, instructions

    Note: Validate instruction sequence
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc get from List with instructions, i
        proc validate_instruction_syntax with analyzer, instruction, i
        proc collect_instruction_info with analyzer, instruction
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Validate required instructions
    proc validate_required_instructions from analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
The Dockerfile spec mandates FROM as the first non-comment instruction
EXCEPT that ARG declarations that supply variables for the FROM line
(e.g., `ARG BASE_TAG` followed by `FROM alpine:${BASE_TAG}`) are
permitted before it. No other instruction may precede FROM because
without a base layer there's nothing for them to act on. We track this
with a single found_from flag rather than an enum because the only
states that matter are "haven't seen FROM yet" and "have seen FROM";
once found, the placement check is satisfied for the rest of the file.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads instruction_count via List.size. Initialises found_from=0, i=0.
Loops while i < count AND found_from == 0: pulls instruction, reads
instruction_type. If type equals "FROM", sets found_from=1 and writes 0
to analyzer offset 72 (current_stage = first stage). Otherwise, tests
for ARG; if NOT ARG, builds an error "FROM instruction must be first
(found <type> at line <i+1>)", adds it, and returns (early exit
because a single misplaced instruction is enough to fail this check).
After the loop, if found_from is still 0, adds "Missing required FROM
instruction".
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_from_instruction_placement" takes analyzer as Integer, instructions as Integer:
    Note: Validate FROM instruction placement and syntax

    Let instruction_count be proc size from List with instructions
    Let found_from be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count and found_from is equal to 0:
        Let instruction be proc get from List with instructions, i
        Let instruction_type be proc get_instruction_type from instruction

        Let is_from be proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction_type, "FROM"
        If is_from is equal to 1:
            Set found_from to 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, 0  Note: Set current_stage to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let is_arg be proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction_type, "ARG"
            If is_arg is equal to 0:
                Note: Non-ARG instruction before FROM
                Let error be "FROM instruction must be first (found "
                Set error to proc string_concat from StringCore with error, instruction_type
                Set error to proc string_concat from StringCore with error, " at line "
                Set error to proc string_concat from StringCore with error, proc int_to_string from StringCore with i plus 1
                Set error to proc string_concat from StringCore with error, ")"
                proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
                Return
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If found_from is equal to 0:
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, "Missing required FROM instruction"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Per-instruction syntax dispatcher. Each Docker instruction kind (FROM,
RUN, COPY, ADD, EXPOSE, ENV, WORKDIR, USER, VOLUME, LABEL, ARG, CMD,
ENTRYPOINT) has its own validator because the argument grammar and
semantic constraints differ. Unknown instructions emit a warning rather
than an error because Docker BuildKit supports extension instructions
via `# syntax=` directives - a hard error would reject valid Dockerfiles
that use newer or third-party frontends.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads instruction_type and args (Lists) from the instruction node. A
Match expression dispatches on the type string to the corresponding
per-instruction validator (validate_from_instruction,
validate_run_instruction, etc.), passing analyzer, args, line_number.
Otherwise branch builds "Unknown instruction: <type> at line <n+1>"
warning and adds it to validation_warnings.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_instruction_syntax" takes analyzer as Integer, instruction as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate individual instruction syntax

    Let instruction_type be proc get_instruction_type from instruction
    Let args be proc get_instruction_arguments from instruction

    Match instruction_type:
        When "FROM":
            proc validate_from_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "RUN":
            proc validate_run_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "COPY":
            proc validate_copy_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "ADD":
            proc validate_add_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "EXPOSE":
            proc validate_expose_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "ENV":
            proc validate_env_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "WORKDIR":
            proc validate_workdir_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "USER":
            proc validate_user_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "VOLUME":
            proc validate_volume_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "LABEL":
            proc validate_label_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "ARG":
            proc validate_arg_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "CMD":
            proc validate_cmd_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        When "ENTRYPOINT":
            proc validate_entrypoint_instruction with analyzer, args, line_number
        Otherwise:
            Let warning be proc string_concat from StringCore with "Unknown instruction: ", instruction_type
            Set warning to proc string_concat from StringCore with warning, " at line "
            Set warning to proc string_concat from StringCore with warning, proc int_to_string from StringCore with line_number plus 1
            proc add_dockerfile_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
FROM accepts two argument shapes: `FROM <image>` for the simple/default-
stage case, and `FROM <image> AS <name>` for multi-stage builds where
the stage gets a referenceable name. Other forms (e.g., 4+ arguments)
indicate a malformed instruction. Stage names registered here populate
analyzer.stages and are looked up by COPY --from=<name> later. The image
reference itself is delegated to validate_image_reference because the
format (registry/repo:tag@digest) is complex enough to warrant its own
parser.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads arg_count via List.size. If 0, builds and adds "FROM instruction
missing image name at line <n+1>" and returns. Reads image_ref at
args[0] and calls validate_image_reference. If arg_count > 2, reads
args[1] (expected "AS") and args[2] (stage name); if args[1] equals
"AS", calls register_build_stage(analyzer, stage_name); otherwise adds
"Invalid FROM syntax, expected AS keyword at line <n+1>".
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Image reference originates from untrusted Dockerfile source. The image
is not pulled or inspected here - only string-validated for format -
so this proc cannot enforce supply-chain policy beyond syntactic
correctness.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_from_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate FROM instruction syntax and image reference

    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args
    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        Let error be "FROM instruction missing image name at line "
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringCore with error, proc int_to_string from StringCore with line_number plus 1
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let image_ref be proc get from List with args, 0
    proc validate_image_reference with analyzer, image_ref, line_number

    Note: Check for stage name in multi-stage builds
    If arg_count is greater than 2:
        Let as_keyword be proc get from List with args, 1
        Let stage_name be proc get from List with args, 2

        Let is_as be proc string_equals from StringCore with as_keyword, "AS"
        If is_as is equal to 1:
            proc register_build_stage with analyzer, stage_name
        Otherwise:
            Set error to "Invalid FROM syntax, expected AS keyword at line "
            Set error to proc string_concat from StringCore with error, proc int_to_string from StringCore with line_number plus 1
            proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
RUN creates a new image layer by executing a shell or exec-form command
at build time, so it has three concerns: syntactic validity, security
implications (running unauthenticated `curl | sh` or installing packages
without GPG verification are well-known attack surfaces), and layer-
cost implications (every RUN adds a layer; combining them with `&&`
reduces image size). The layer_count counter is bumped here so that
analyze_layer_optimization can detect when too many separate RUN
layers exist.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads arg_count via List.size. If 0, adds "RUN instruction missing
command at line <n+1>" and returns. Reads command at args[0]. Calls
check_run_security_patterns(analyzer, command, line_number) which
scans for known anti-patterns. Calls
analyze_run_layer_optimization(analyzer, command, line_number) which
warns when commands could be combined. Reads layer_count at offset 80,
increments and writes back - the analyser's tally for later phase 5.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Command string is untrusted input from the Dockerfile. The security
pattern scanner here is best-effort heuristic; it should not be
treated as a guarantee of safety - manual review remains required for
production images.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_run_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate RUN instruction and analyze for security issues

    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args
    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        Let error be "RUN instruction missing command at line "
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringCore with error, proc int_to_string from StringCore with line_number plus 1
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let command be proc get from List with args, 0

    Note: Check for security anti-patterns
    proc check_run_security_patterns with analyzer, command, line_number

    Note: Check for layer optimization opportunities
    proc analyze_run_layer_optimization with analyzer, command, line_number

    Note: Increment layer count
    Let current_layers be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80, current_layers plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
COPY requires at least one source and exactly one destination - the LAST
arg is always the destination, regardless of how many sources precede
it. This shape (`COPY src1 src2 ... dest`) lets a single COPY layer
bring in multiple files. We must validate each source/dest pair against
security patterns (no copying credentials/keys/secrets into images) and
also handle the multi-stage form `COPY --from=stage src dest` which is
parsed but not specifically validated here (analyze_stage_dependencies
catches stage-reference errors). Layer count bumps because each COPY is
its own layer in Docker's storage driver.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads arg_count. If < 2 (need at least source + dest), adds "COPY
instruction requires source and destination at line <n+1>" and returns.
Reads destination at args[arg_count-1]. Loops i in 0..arg_count-2:
reads source at args[i], calls
check_copy_security_patterns(analyzer, source, destination, line_number).
Reads layer_count at offset 80, increments and persists.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Source paths originate from untrusted Dockerfile source. Pattern
matching catches common credential-leak antipatterns (e.g. `.ssh/`,
`.aws/`, `id_rsa`, `.env`) but is not exhaustive; explicit `.dockerignore`
remains the authoritative defense.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_copy_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate COPY instruction syntax and paths

    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args
    If arg_count is less than 2:
        Let error be "COPY instruction requires source and destination at line "
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringCore with error, proc int_to_string from StringCore with line_number plus 1
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let destination be proc get from List with args, arg_count minus 1

    Note: Check for security issues in paths
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arg_count minus 1:
        Let source be proc get from List with args, i
        proc check_copy_security_patterns with analyzer, source, destination, line_number
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Increment layer count
    Let current_layers be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80, current_layers plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
EXPOSE declares container-facing ports; we must reject empty arg lists and
non-numeric/out-of-range port specs so downstream tooling (compose, runtime
port maps) never receives a malformed declaration. Valid specs are appended
to the analyzer's exposed_ports list at offset 16 for later aggregation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
After confirming at least one arg, walks args via List.size/get, delegating
each entry to validate_port_specification (which handles single and
PORT/PROTO forms). Valid entries are added to the analyzer's exposed_ports
list (offset 16); invalid ones generate a validation error pointing to the
1-based line number.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Args originate from untrusted Dockerfile text. Validation rejects anything
outside 1..65535 to prevent passing bogus port specs to runtime tooling.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_expose_instruction" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer, line_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate EXPOSE instruction and track exposed ports

    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args
    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        Let error be "EXPOSE instruction missing port number at line "
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringCore with error, proc int_to_string from StringCore with line_number plus 1
        proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let exposed_ports be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than arg_count:
        Let port_spec be proc get from List with args, i
        Let is_valid_port be proc validate_port_specification from port_spec

        If is_valid_port is equal to 1:
            proc add from List with exposed_ports, port_spec
        Otherwise:
            Set error to "Invalid port specification '"
            Set error to proc string_concat from StringCore with error, port_spec
            Set error to proc string_concat from StringCore with error, "' at line "
            Set error to proc string_concat from StringCore with error, proc int_to_string from StringCore with line_number plus 1
            proc add_dockerfile_validation_error with analyzer, error
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: BUILD STAGE ANALYSIS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 2 builds the stage dependency graph by running four sub-analyses
in fixed order: identify_build_stages populates analyzer.stages (must
run first - everything else reads from this list), analyze_stage_dependencies
walks COPY --from references to construct the dependency edges,
check_unused_stages flags stages that no later stage references (waste of
build time), validate_stage_references catches forward references and
self-references which Docker treats as errors. The ordering is strict:
references can't be validated until the stage set is known, and unused-
stage detection needs the dependency graph already built.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls four procs in sequence:
identify_build_stages(analyzer, dockerfile_ast) which populates the
stages List (offset 8) from FROM instructions with optional AS clauses;
analyze_stage_dependencies(analyzer, dockerfile_ast) which walks COPY
--from to add edges; check_unused_stages(analyzer) which is registry-
only (no ast); validate_stage_references(analyzer, dockerfile_ast).
No return value - results flow into the analyzer's security_issues and
optimization_warnings lists.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_build_stages" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Analyze multi-stage build structure and dependencies

    proc identify_build_stages with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc analyze_stage_dependencies with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc check_unused_stages from analyzer
    proc validate_stage_references with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-stage builds are recognised by FROM <image> [AS <name>] occurrences;
this pass populates analyzer.stages (offset 8) with one entry per FROM so
later passes can validate stage references and detect unused stages. Unnamed
FROMs receive a synthetic "stage<N>" label so downstream graph code can
treat every stage uniformly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks the instruction list once. For each FROM with arg_count > 2 (image
plus AS plus name), pushes args[2] onto the stages list; otherwise pushes
"stage" concatenated with the running stage_count. stage_count is local —
the list itself is the durable record.
@End Implementation

Process called "identify_build_stages" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Identify all build stages in the Dockerfile

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions from dockerfile_ast
    Let instruction_count be proc size from List with instructions
    Let stages be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let stage_count be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc get from List with instructions, i
        Let instruction_type be proc get_instruction_type from instruction

        Let is_from be proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction_type, "FROM"
        If is_from is equal to 1:
            Let args be proc get_instruction_arguments from instruction
            Let arg_count be proc size from List with args

            If arg_count is greater than 2:
                Let stage_name be proc get from List with args, 2
                proc add from List with stages, stage_name
                Set stage_count to stage_count plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Note: Unnamed stage
                Let default_name be proc string_concat from StringCore with "stage", proc int_to_string from StringCore with stage_count
                proc add from List with stages, default_name
                Set stage_count to stage_count plus 1
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cross-stage COPY references (`COPY --from=stage_name src dest`) are the
only way one Docker stage references another, so this dependency walk
focuses exclusively on COPY instructions. The current_stage counter
starts at 0 and bumps on each FROM, giving each instruction a known
home stage. Stage dependencies flow backwards in source order: a COPY
in stage N can reference stage M only if M < N. The detector here
counts FROM occurrences to maintain current_stage, and dispatches each
COPY to analyze_copy_stage_dependency which actually examines the
--from argument.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads instructions list and its count. Initialises current_stage=0 and
i=0. Loops: reads instruction at index i and its instruction_type. If
type equals "FROM", bumps current_stage by 1. Otherwise tests for "COPY";
if matched, calls analyze_copy_stage_dependency(analyzer, instruction,
current_stage). Other types are skipped (they can't reference stages).
The current_stage value is local because we just need the running index,
not a persistent state.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_stage_dependencies" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Analyze dependencies between build stages

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions from dockerfile_ast
    Let instruction_count be proc size from List with instructions
    Let current_stage be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc get from List with instructions, i
        Let instruction_type be proc get_instruction_type from instruction

        Let is_from be proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction_type, "FROM"
        If is_from is equal to 1:
            Set current_stage to current_stage plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Let is_copy be proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction_type, "COPY"
            If is_copy is equal to 1:
                proc analyze_copy_stage_dependency with analyzer, instruction, current_stage
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: SECURITY ANALYSIS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 4 runs four orthogonal security sub-checks: user privileges
(detecting root-running containers, the #1 container security CWE),
sensitive data exposure (catching secrets baked into image layers via
ENV or COPY), package security (insecure download/install patterns),
and general best-practice security policy (e.g., no SETUID binaries,
no curl-to-bash piping). Each sub-check is independent so they can run
in any order; we chose this order because user privileges and sensitive
data are the highest-frequency issues in CVE reports.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls four sub-checks sequentially: check_user_privileges (scans for
USER instructions), check_sensitive_data_exposure (walks COPY, ENV,
LABEL for credential-shaped strings), check_package_security (scans
RUN commands for unsafe package-manager invocations),
validate_security_best_practices (the policy aggregator). All findings
flow into analyzer.security_issues (offset 88). No return value.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
This phase is the primary defense against image security issues found
post-build. The checks here are pattern-based and best-effort;
production deployments must additionally run dedicated scanners
(Trivy, Grype, etc.) against the built image.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "analyze_dockerfile_security" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Perform comprehensive security analysis

    proc check_user_privileges with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc check_sensitive_data_exposure with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc check_package_security with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc validate_security_best_practices with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
End Process

@Reasoning:
Docker containers default to running as root (UID 0) if no USER
instruction overrides it - and root inside a container has near-host
privileges when combined with `--privileged` or volume mounts. This
check walks the instruction list noting the most recent USER, and at
the end determines whether the FINAL effective user is root (either
"root" / "0" string match or no USER instruction at all). Only the
LAST USER matters for the running container - intermediate USER changes
during build are not the security concern; what runs in production is.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initialises has_user_instruction=0, current_user="root", i=0. Loops
instruction list: reads instruction_type, tests for "USER". On match
sets has_user_instruction=1, reads instruction's args; if args has
content, updates current_user to args[0]. After the loop, tests if
current_user equals "root" OR has_user_instruction equals 0. Either
condition adds "Container running as root user - security risk" to
analyzer.security_issues (offset 88).
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Detection is string-comparison only - "root", "0", and "ROOT" are
matched, but a hostile actor could craft `USER 0:0` or use numeric
forms not caught by the simple match. This is a defense-in-depth
hint, not a complete privilege analysis.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "check_user_privileges" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Check for privilege escalation and root usage

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions from dockerfile_ast
    Let instruction_count be proc size from List with instructions
    Let has_user_instruction be 0
    Let current_user be "root"
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc get from List with instructions, i
        Let instruction_type be proc get_instruction_type from instruction

        Let is_user be proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction_type, "USER"
        If is_user is equal to 1:
            Set has_user_instruction to 1
            Let args be proc get_instruction_arguments from instruction
            Let arg_count be proc size from List with args

            If arg_count is greater than 0:
                Set current_user to proc get from List with args, 0
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Check if running as root in final stage
    Let is_root be proc string_equals from StringCore with current_user, "root"
    If is_root is equal to 1 or has_user_instruction is equal to 0:
        Let security_issues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
        proc add from List with security_issues, "Container running as root user - security risk"
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: LAYER OPTIMIZATION ANALYSIS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 5 examines layer-economy concerns: each layer in a Docker image
adds storage overhead, slows cold pulls, and bloats the image graph in
registries. The three sub-checks address: (1) RUN-combining (consecutive
RUNs should be merged with `&&` to share one layer), (2) cache-friendly
ordering (instructions that change rarely should appear before those
that change often, maximising cache hits during incremental builds),
(3) layer-ordering policy (e.g., COPY application code AFTER package
installs so app-only changes don't bust the install cache).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls three sub-procedures: check_run_command_combining (counts
consecutive RUN instructions, warns when > 1),
analyze_cache_efficiency (scans for ordering anti-patterns),
check_layer_ordering (validates standard Docker layer-ordering
recommendations). All findings flow into
analyzer.optimization_warnings (offset 96). No return value.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_layer_optimization" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Analyze layer optimization opportunities

    proc check_run_command_combining with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc analyze_cache_efficiency with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc check_layer_ordering with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
End Process

@Reasoning:
Each RUN instruction creates a distinct image layer with full filesystem
state. Three consecutive `RUN apt-get install ...`, `RUN apt-get install ...`,
`RUN apt-get install ...` instructions creates three layers when one
combined RUN with `&&` would produce one. Beyond size savings, combining
is also a SECURITY measure: temporary files (e.g., apt cache) created
in one RUN persist into the layer even if a later RUN deletes them,
because layers are append-only - only combining the create and delete
into a single RUN actually removes them from the image. We count runs
of CONSECUTIVE RUN instructions; non-RUN instructions reset the counter.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads instructions and its count. Initialises consecutive_runs=0 and
i=0. Loops: reads instruction_type. If equals "RUN", bumps
consecutive_runs. Otherwise: if consecutive_runs > 1, builds warning
"<n> consecutive RUN commands could be combined into one layer" and
appends to optimization_warnings (offset 96), then resets
consecutive_runs to 0. After loop: handles the trailing case - if the
file ends with consecutive_runs > 1, adds "<n> consecutive RUN commands
at end could be combined".
@End Implementation

Process called "check_run_command_combining" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Check for consecutive RUN commands that could be combined

    Let instructions be proc get_dockerfile_instructions from dockerfile_ast
    Let instruction_count be proc size from List with instructions
    Let consecutive_runs be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instruction_count:
        Let instruction be proc get from List with instructions, i
        Let instruction_type be proc get_instruction_type from instruction

        Let is_run be proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction_type, "RUN"
        If is_run is equal to 1:
            Set consecutive_runs to consecutive_runs plus 1
        Otherwise:
            If consecutive_runs is greater than 1:
                Let optimization_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
                Let warning be proc int_to_string from StringCore with consecutive_runs
                Set warning to proc string_concat from StringCore with warning, " consecutive RUN commands could be combined into one layer"
                proc add from List with optimization_warnings, warning
            End If
            Set consecutive_runs to 0
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Check final sequence
    If consecutive_runs is greater than 1:
        Set optimization_warnings to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
        Set warning to proc int_to_string from StringCore with consecutive_runs
        Set warning to proc string_concat from StringCore with warning, " consecutive RUN commands at end could be combined"
        proc add from List with optimization_warnings, warning
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: DOCKER BEST PRACTICES VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 6 (final) is the catch-all best-practices aggregator covering
issues that don't fit into the previous five specific phases: base
image selection (avoid `latest`, prefer slim/alpine, avoid deprecated
images), HEALTHCHECK presence (production containers should declare
liveness probes), signal handling (PID 1 inside containers needs to
forward SIGTERM correctly for graceful shutdown), and metadata
completeness (LABEL maintainer, org.opencontainers.image.* labels for
provenance). Each of these is a soft policy concern - violations don't
break builds but flag the image as non-production-ready.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls four sub-procs: check_base_image_best_practices(analyzer) which
consults the already-populated base_images registry,
check_healthcheck_configuration(analyzer, dockerfile_ast) which scans
for HEALTHCHECK instructions, validate_signal_handling(analyzer,
dockerfile_ast) which checks ENTRYPOINT/CMD shell vs exec form and
related concerns, check_metadata_completeness(analyzer) which audits
labels and args. All findings go to optimization_warnings or
security_issues depending on severity.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_docker_best_practices" takes analyzer as Integer, dockerfile_ast as Integer:
    Note: Validate Docker best practices compliance

    proc check_base_image_best_practices from analyzer
    proc check_healthcheck_configuration with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc validate_signal_handling with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    proc check_metadata_completeness from analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two image-reference anti-patterns flagged here: (1) the `:latest` tag
which is a moving target - the image rebuilt tomorrow may be different
from today's, making builds non-reproducible AND creating a supply-chain
attack vector if the upstream maintainer is compromised; (2) entirely
missing tag, which Docker silently resolves to `:latest` with the same
problems. Both are reported but at different severities: `:latest` is
a security issue (someone deliberately chose it), missing tag is an
optimization warning (likely a forgot-to-pin oversight).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads base_images list (analyzer offset 0) and its count. Loops i in
0..count-1: reads image_ref at index i. First substring test:
string_contains(image_ref, ":latest"); on match appends "Base image
uses 'latest' tag: <ref>" to security_issues (offset 88). Second
test: string_contains(image_ref, ":"); if FALSE (no tag at all),
appends "Base image missing explicit tag: <ref>" to
optimization_warnings (offset 96). Both checks fire independently;
a `foo:latest` reference fails only the first; a `foo` reference
fails only the second.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
The `:latest` tag check is the primary supply-chain defense in this
analyzer; combined with a registry-side immutable-tag policy and
SBOM generation, it forms the syntactic-side of provenance enforcement.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "check_base_image_best_practices" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Check base image selection best practices

    Let base_images be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let image_count be proc size from List with base_images
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than image_count:
        Let image_ref be proc get from List with base_images, i

        Note: Check for 'latest' tag
        Let has_latest be proc string_contains from StringCore with image_ref, ":latest"
        If has_latest is equal to 1:
            Let security_issues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
            Let issue be proc string_concat from StringCore with "Base image uses 'latest' tag: ", image_ref
            proc add from List with security_issues, issue
        End If

        Note: Check for missing tag
        Let has_colon be proc string_contains from StringCore with image_ref, ":"
        If has_colon is equal to 0:
            Let optimization_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
            Let warning be proc string_concat from StringCore with "Base image missing explicit tag: ", image_ref
            proc add from List with optimization_warnings, warning
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: UTILITY FUNCTIONS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Docker EXPOSE arguments accept three formats: a bare port (`80`), port
with protocol (`80/tcp` or `80/udp`), or port range (`8080-8090` or
`8080-8090/tcp`). Other protocols (sctp, etc.) are not standard Docker
and are rejected. The dash-separated range form requires BOTH endpoints
to parse as integers in 1..65535 - we do not enforce start < end here
because Docker accepts both orders and normalises. Returning Integer
0/1 lets the caller branch cleanly without parsing diagnostic strings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Locates `/` via string_find. If found, splits into port_part (before)
and protocol_part (after); checks protocol_part equals "tcp" or "udp",
returning 0 on any other value. Then operates on port_part. Locates
`-`; if found, splits into start_port and end_port substrings and
validates each as a valid port number via is_valid_port_number,
returning 0 if either fails. If no dash, validates port_part directly.
Returns 1 only when every component passes.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Port spec originates from untrusted Dockerfile source. Strict
1..65535 validation prevents downstream tooling from receiving
out-of-range values that could underflow/overflow into kernel-managed
port tables.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_port_specification" takes port_spec as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Validate Docker port specification format

    Let slash_pos be proc string_find from StringCore with port_spec, "/"
    Let port_part be port_spec

    If slash_pos is not equal to -1:
        Set port_part to proc string_substring from StringCore with port_spec, 0, slash_pos
        Let protocol_part be proc string_substring from StringCore with port_spec, slash_pos plus 1, proc string_length from StringCore with port_spec minus slash_pos minus 1

        Note: Validate protocol
        Let is_tcp be proc string_equals from StringCore with protocol_part, "tcp"
        Let is_udp be proc string_equals from StringCore with protocol_part, "udp"
        If is_tcp is equal to 0 and is_udp is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for port range
    Let dash_pos be proc string_find from StringCore with port_part, "-"
    If dash_pos is not equal to -1:
        Let start_port be proc string_substring from StringCore with port_part, 0, dash_pos
        Let end_port be proc string_substring from StringCore with port_part, dash_pos plus 1, proc string_length from StringCore with port_part minus dash_pos minus 1

        Let start_valid be proc is_valid_port_number from start_port
        Let end_valid be proc is_valid_port_number from end_port

        Return start_valid and end_valid
    End If

    Note: Single port number
    Return proc is_valid_port_number from port_part
End Process

@Reasoning:
Final numeric check for an EXPOSE port: a 1..65535 decimal integer with at
most 5 characters (length cap is a quick reject for over-long strings even
if all-digit). Pure validator returning 0/1 — does not raise diagnostics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three gates: length in 1..5, every byte in '0'..'9' (ASCII 48..57), and the
parsed integer in 1..65535. Uses string_char_at/string_to_int from
StringCore; no allocations beyond what those calls perform internally.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_valid_port_number" takes port_str as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if string is valid port number (1-65535)

    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with port_str
    If length is equal to 0 or length is greater than 5:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check all characters are digits
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with port_str, i
        If char is less than 48 or char is greater than 57:  Note: Not a digit
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Convert to number and check range
    Let port_num be proc string_to_int from StringCore with port_str
    If port_num is less than 1 or port_num is greater than 65535:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ERROR HANDLING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Records the first fatal failure that aborts further analysis (e.g. impossible
AST shape). Distinct from add_dockerfile_validation_error which collects
recoverable issues; this one trips the sticky has_error flag.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Writes the error_message string handle into offset 120 and sets has_error=1
at offset 128. Caller's StringCore is borrowed - the analyzer's destructor
frees it.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_dockerfile_semantic_error" takes analyzer as Integer, error_message as Integer:
    Note: Set semantic analysis error

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120, error_message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128, 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validation errors accumulate without aborting analysis so the user gets the
full set in one pass (missing FROM, bare ADD without --chown, etc.).
Append-only ordering preserves source-document order in the report.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads validation_errors List from offset 104 and appends the error_message
string handle. The analyzer's destructor walks the list and frees each
string.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_dockerfile_validation_error" takes analyzer as Integer, error_message as Integer:
    Note: Add validation error to error list

    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104
    proc add from List with errors, error_message
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mirror of the error-add path for warning-level issues (e.g. apt-get without
--no-install-recommends, root USER in production). Kept in a separate List
so warning-only builds proceed and the reporter applies distinct formatting.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads validation_warnings List from offset 112 and appends the warning
message string. Same ownership semantics as add_dockerfile_validation_error.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_dockerfile_validation_warning" takes analyzer as Integer, warning_message as Integer:
    Note: Add validation warning to warning list

    Let warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112
    proc add from List with warnings, warning_message
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PUBLIC API
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
One-shot facade used by the build driver: allocates analyzer + runs analysis
+ returns the populated analyzer for downstream consumption. Caller owns the
returned analyzer and must free it via destroy_dockerfile_semantic_analyzer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls create_dockerfile_semantic_analyzer; on OOM returns 0 (analyzer is the
public artifact, so a null result means analysis could not even start).
Otherwise runs analyze_dockerfile which walks the AST and populates every
registry/diagnostic stream, then returns the analyzer.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
dockerfile_ast originates from user-supplied Dockerfiles which often contain
URLs, secrets in ARG defaults, and shell commands. Analysis itself is read-
only over the AST; the diagnostic stream may carry attacker-controlled
strings which the reporter must escape before display.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "dockerfile_semantic_analyze" takes dockerfile_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform semantic analysis on Dockerfile AST

    Let analyzer be proc create_dockerfile_semantic_analyzer
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let result be proc analyze_dockerfile with analyzer, dockerfile_ast
    Return analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public accessor for the validation_errors stream so the diagnostic emitter
or IDE bridge can render the full error set without poking analyzer
internals. Null analyzer returns 0 (treated as no-errors) so callers can
chain accessors safely.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads offset 104 (validation_errors List). Borrowed pointer - analyzer
retains ownership.
@End Implementation

Process called "dockerfile_semantic_get_errors" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get validation errors from semantic analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public accessor for warnings list. Separation from errors is preserved at
the API surface so IDEs can group/filter independently and reporters can
emit distinct exit codes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads offset 112 (validation_warnings List). Borrowed pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "dockerfile_semantic_get_warnings" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get validation warnings from semantic analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112
End Process

@Reasoning:
Security findings (e.g. USER root, ADD instead of COPY with checksum, ENV
secrets, --privileged hints) are collected on their own stream so security
tooling can subscribe to them without parsing free-form warning text.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads offset 88 (security_issues List). Borrowed pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "dockerfile_semantic_get_security_issues" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get security issues found during analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
End Process

@Reasoning:
Layer-count and instruction-ordering advice (combine RUNs, place COPY late,
multi-stage builds, etc.) lives on a dedicated optimization stream so users
can opt into "size hints" without seeing them in a normal warning report.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads offset 96 (optimization_warnings List). Borrowed pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "dockerfile_semantic_get_optimization_warnings" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get optimization warnings from analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
End Process

@Reasoning:
Drivers need a single integer "did analysis pass" signal. Returns the actual
error count rather than 0/1 so reporters can pretty-print "N errors". A
null analyzer is treated as 1 error to keep the "analyzer-failed" path
indistinguishable from "errors found" at the call site.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null analyzer returns 1. Otherwise reads validation_errors at offset 104 and
returns its List.size, which is 0 when analysis succeeded with no errors.
@End Implementation

Process called "dockerfile_semantic_has_errors" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if semantic analysis found any errors

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104
    Let error_count be proc size from List with errors
    Return error_count
End Process